<section id="random-energy-model" class="level1">
<h1>Random Energy Model</h1>
<p>Here we do a tutorial calculation of the random energy model. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0AZ%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cexp(-%20%5Cbeta%20E_%7Bi%7D)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"></p>
<p>where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?E_i%20%5Csim%20%5Cmathcal%20N(0,%20N/2)"> iid. Our replica partition function becomes <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20Z%5En%20&amp;%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%20=%201%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cexp(-%20%5Cbeta%20E_%7Bi_1%7D%20-%20...%20-%20%5Cbeta%20E_%7Bi_n%7D)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> The configuration of the replicated system is given by a tuple <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(i_1,%20...,%20i_n)"> where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i_%5Calpha%20%5Cin%20%5C%7B1,%20...,%202%5EN%5C%7D">. So there are a total of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?2%5E%7BN%5En%7D"> possible configurations. A convient way of re-expressing this is to insert the identity in the form of the indicator function <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1%20=%20%5Csum_%7Ba=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20j)"> (this holds when <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?j%20%5Cin%20%5C%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%5C%7D">) <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20Z%5En%20&amp;%20=%20%20%5Csum_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%20=%201%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%20%5Cexp%20%5Cleft%20(-%20%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cbeta%20E_j%20%5Csum_%7Ba=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20j)%5Cright)%20%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%20=%201%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cprod_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cexp%20%5Cleft%20(-%20%5Cbeta%20E_j%20%5Csum_%7Ba=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20j)%5Cright)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%20I"> is the indicator function. We can now take the expectation value over <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?E_i">, as we assumed iid, so it factorizes. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%20=%201%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cprod_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cexp%20%5Cleft%20(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2N%7D%7B4%7D%20%5Cleft%20%5B%5Csum_%7Ba=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20j)%20%20%5Cright%5D%5E2%5Cright)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> Note that <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%5Cleft%20%5B%5Csum_%7Ba=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20j)%20%20%5Cright%5D%5E2%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bj=1%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20j)%20%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_b%20=%20j)%20=%20%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20i_b)">. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%20=%201%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%20%5Cexp%20%5Cleft%20(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2N%7D%7B4%7D%20%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20i_b)%20%5Cright)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> If we interpret this directly, the energy of the entire replica system now looks like <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?E_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B-%5Cbeta%20N%7D%7B4%7D%20%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20i_b)">. So after quenching the replicas “interact” (I precisely mean the energy does not factorize over addition <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?E_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%7D%20%5Cneq%20%5Csum_a%20E_%7Bi_a%7D">).</p>
<p>Now we introduce the <strong>overlap matrix</strong> <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Bab%7D%20%5Cequiv%20%5Cmathbb%20I(i_a%20=%20i_b)"> where the entries <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cin%20%5C%7B0,%201%5C%7D"> (because they’re given by indicator function). The name matrix is a misnomer, this should really be a tensor, as we can iterate in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i_a%20%5Cin%20%5C%7B1,%20...,%202%5EN%5C%7D%20~%20%5Cforall%20a">. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D%20&amp;%20=%20%20%5Csum_%7Bi_1,%20...,%20i_n%20=%201%7D%5E%7B2%5EN%7D%20%5Cexp%20%5Cleft%20(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2N%7D%7B4%7D%20%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20Q_%7Bab%7D(i_1,%20...,%20i_n)%20%5Cright)%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Csum_%7BQ%7D%20%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q)%20%5Cexp%5Cleft%20(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2N%7D%7B4%7D%20%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20Q_%7Bab%7D%20%5Cright)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"></p>
<ul>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q)"> is the number of configurations (where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(i_1,%20...,%20i_n)"> denotes the microstates, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q"> is the macrostate generated by said microstates).</li>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csum_Q"> runs over all symmetric matrices with all ones on the diagonal, and the off diagonal only contains <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B0%20,1%5C%7D">. There are <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%20(n-1)/2"> degrees of freedom, hence there are <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?2%5E%7Bn%20(n-1)/2%7D"> configurations.</li>
</ul>
<p>Because the number of configurations is exponential (in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N">), we can rewrite <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathcal%20N_N"> in large-deviation form. This is fancy words for we insert the identity in the form <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cexp%20%5Clog%20(%5Ccdot)%20=%201">. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q)%20=%20%5Cexp(%5Clog%20(%5Cmathcal%20N_N%20(Q))%20%5Cdoteq%20%5Cexp(N%20s(Q))%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?s(Q)%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Clog(%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q))"> is the entropy density (we’ll always apply Stirling’s approximations to this thing),.</p>
<p>An abridged expression for our quenched partition fucntion is <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D%20=%20%5Csum_%7BQ%7D%20%5Cexp(N%20g(Q))">, where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(Q)%20%5Cequiv%20s(Q)%20+%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2%7D%7B4%7D%5Csum_%7Ba,b=1%7D%5En%20Q_%7Bab%7D">. Now, our method of attack is to estimate the sum using saddle point. We must proceed carefully because sometimes the saddle point exhibits <strong>replica symmetry breaking</strong>!</p>
<section id="replica-symmetry-solution" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="replica-symmetry-solution">Replica Symmetry Solution</h2>
<p><strong>Definition (Replica Symmetry (Breaking)):</strong> At the beginning of the calculation, we assumed replicas are statistically independent. So that means we can permute our replicas at no cost. Stated formally, let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cpi"> is some permutation operator. When the dominant saddle point exhibits <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20g(Q_%7B%5Cpi(a),%20%5Cpi(b)%7D)%20=%20g(Q)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> the system has <strong>replica symmetry</strong>.</p>
<p>In the case where we have replica symmetry, this fixes <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q"> as it’s entries should be invariant under permutation. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Baa%7D%20=%20%5Calpha">, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Bab%7D%20=%20%5Cbeta"> for all combinations <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?a%5Cneq%20b">. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20Q%20=%20%5Cbegin%7Bpmatrix%7D%0A%20%20%20%20%5Calpha%20&amp;%20%5Cbeta%20&amp;%20%5Cbeta%20&amp;%20%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cbeta%20&amp;%20%5Calpha%20&amp;%20%5Cbeta%20&amp;%20...%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cbeta%20&amp;%20%5Cbeta%20&amp;%20%5Calpha%20&amp;%20%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20&amp;%20%5Cvdots%20&amp;%20%20&amp;%20%5Cddots%0A%20%20%5Cend%7Bpmatrix%7D%20=%20(%5Calpha%20-%20%5Cbeta)%20%5Cmathbb%20I%20+%20%5Cbeta%20%20~%20xx%5ET,%20&amp;&amp;%20%5Ctext%7Bwhere%20%7D%20x%20=%20(1,1,...)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> Hence it should look like an identity plus a rank 1 correction.</p>
<p>However, by some law I saw in <code>Interstelar (2014)</code>, if something can go wrong, it will go wrong. And in physics, it goes extra crazy. <strong>Replica symmetry can be spontaneously broken</strong> in the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty"> limit (analogous to the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%20Z_2"> symmetry breaking exhibits by the Curie-Weiss model). We’ll see this in action in the next section…</p>
<p>Going back to our problem, let’s analyze the entires of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q"> assuming replica symmetry. We already know the diagonal <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Baa%7D%20=%201">, what about the off-diagonal. Well recall entries can only take in two values <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Bab%7D%20%5Cin%20%5C%7B0,%201%5C%7D">:</p>
<ul>
<li>For <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Bab%7D%20=%200">, we’ll denote these solutions as <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7BRS,0%7D">. Then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q_%7BRS,0%7D)%20&amp;%20=%20%5Cprod_%7B%5Calpha=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20(2%5EN%20-%20%5Calpha)%20%5C%5C%0As(Q_%7BRS,0%7D)%20&amp;%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Csum_%7B%5Calpha%20=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20%5Clog(2%5EN%20-%20%5Calpha)%20%5Capprox%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Csum_%7B%5Calpha%20=%200%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20%5Clog(2%5EN)%20=%20n%20%5Clog%202%5C%5C%0Ag_0(%5Cbeta,%20n)%20%5Cequiv%20g(Q_%7BRS,0%7D)%20&amp;%20=%20n%20(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2%7D%7B4%7D%20+%20%5Clog%202)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"></li>
<li>For <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Bab%7D%20=%201">, we’ll denote these solutions as <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7BRS,1%7D">. Then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q_%7BRS,1%7D)%20&amp;%20=%202%5EN%5C%5C%0As(Q_%7BRS,1%7D)%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clog%202%5C%5C%0Ag_1(%5Cbeta,%20n)%20%5Cequiv%20g(Q_%7BRS,1%7D)%20&amp;%20=%20%5Cfrac%7Bn%5E2%20%5Cbeta%5E2%7D%7B4%7D%20+%20%5Clog%202%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"></li>
</ul>
<p>Because we’re approximating this as a saddle point, our solution will be dictated by becomes <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Ctext%7Bmax%7D%5Bg_0(%5Cbeta,%20n),%20g_1(%5Cbeta,%20n)%5D">. Interpretation-wise, we can say there’s a phase-transition between the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_0"> solution and the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_1"> solution, which is <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta_c(n)%20=%20%5Csqrt%7B4%20%5Clog%202%20/n%7D"></p>
<ul>
<li>When <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%20%3E%201">:
<ul>
<li>If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta%20%3E%20%5Cbeta_c"> (low temperature phase), then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_1%20%3E%20g_0">. The <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_1"> solution dominates, all replicas are locked together.</li>
<li>If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta%20%3C%20%5Cbeta_c"> (high temperature phase), then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_0%20%3C%20g_1">. The <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_0"> solution dominates, hence all replicas are independent.</li>
</ul></li>
<li>When <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%20%3C%201">, which is the limit we’ll eventually take, the phases flip (in temperature!)
<ul>
<li><p>If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta%20%3E%20%5Cbeta_c"> (low temperature phase), then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_1%20%3C%20g_0">.</p></li>
<li><p>If <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta%20%3C%20%5Cbeta_c"> (high temperature phase), then <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g_0%20%3E%20g_1">.</p>
<p>Replicas becomes independent at low temperatures, and correlated at high temperatures. Wait whaaaat? We’ve previously stated that they are correlated…</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>In the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%3C%201"> regime, replica trick requires us to use the minimum of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(Q)">… There is no mathematical justification for this.</p>
<p>Let’s compute the free energy now <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20-%20%5Cbeta%20f%20&amp;%20%5Cequiv%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Cmathbb%20E%20%5B%5Clog%20Z%5D%20%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Clim_%7Bn%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%20n%7D%20%5Clog%20(%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D)%20&amp;%20%5Ctext%7BReplica%20trick%20formula%7D%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7Bn%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%20n%7D%20%5Clog%20(%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D)%20%20&amp;%20%5Ctext%7BInterchange%20limits%20(non%20rigorous)%7D%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7Bn%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Cfrac%7Bg_0(n,%20%5Cbeta)%7D%7Bn%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2%7D%7B4%7D%20+%20%5Clog%202%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> We have recovered the low temperature phase <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta%20%3E%20%5Cbeta_c">, but it misses the existence of the phase transition. In general, the RS solution isn’t able to find the low temperature phase.</p>
</section>
<section id="one-step-replica-symmetry-breaking-1rsb-solution" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="one-step-replica-symmetry-breaking-1rsb-solution">One-Step Replica-Symmetry Breaking (1RSB) Solution</h2>
<p>To recover the lower temperature phase, perhaps the system breaks replica symmetry! So how do we find these new saddle points? We’ll use <strong>one-step replica symmetry break</strong>.</p>
<p>The idea is to suppose <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> is a multiple of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x">, divide the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> replicas into <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n/x"> groups of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x"> elements, and now set <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign*%7D%0A%20%20%20%20Q_%7Baa%7D%20&amp;=%20%5Calpha_1%20%20&amp;%5Ctext%7BIn%20this%20problem%20it%20is%201%7D%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20Q_%7Bab%7D%20&amp;%20=%20%5Cbeta_1%20&amp;%20%5Ctext%7BIf%20$a$%20and%20$b$%20are%20in%20the%20same%20group%7D%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20Q_%7Bab%7D%20&amp;%20=%20%5Cgamma_1%20&amp;%20%5Ctext%7BIf%20$a$%20and%20$b$%20are%20NOT%20in%20the%20same%20group%7D%0A%5Cend%7Balign*%7D"> Recall for for this problem, it’s a symmetric matrix with elements in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B0,1%5C%7D">. So <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Baa%7D%20%20=%201">, and this ansatz is only different if we allow <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbeta_1%20=%201"> and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cgamma_1%20=%200">.</p>
<p>So now our indices becomes <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i_1%20=%20...%20=%20i_x">, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i_%7Bx+1%7D%20=%20...%20=%20i_%7B2x%7D">. The number of microstates <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(i_1,%20...,%20i_n)"> which satsify this becomes <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20%5Cmathcal%20N_N(Q)%20&amp;=%202%5EN%20%5Ctimes%20(2%5EN%20-%20%201)%20%5Ctimes%20...%20%5Ctimes%20(2%5EN%20-%20n/x%20%20+1%20)%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20s(Q)%20&amp;=%20(n/x)%20%5Clog%202%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20g_%7B1RSB%7D(%5Cbeta,%20n,%20x)%20&amp;%20=%20n%20(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta%5E2%7D%7B4%7D%20x%20+%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bx%7D%20%5Clog%202)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> So now we’ll minimize this (recall our discussion / example earlier). Minimizing w.r.t. <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x"> yields <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20x_*%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B2%20%5Csqrt%7B%5Clog%202%7D%7D%7B%5Cbeta%7D%20=%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Cbeta_c%7D%7B%5Cbeta%7D%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> We can now compute our free energy <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20-%20%5Cbeta%20f%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D%5Cmathbb%20E%5B%5Clog%20Z%5D%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%20%5Clim_%7Bn%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BNn%7D%20%5Clog(%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D)%20%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7Bn%20%5Cto%200%7D%5Clim_%7BN%20%5Cto%20%5Cinfty%7D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BNn%7D%20%5Clog(%5Cmathbb%20E%5BZ%5En%5D)%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Clim_%7Bn%20%5Cto%200%7D%20%5Cmin_x%20%5Cfrac%7Bg_%7B1%7BRSB%7D%7D(%5Cbeta,%20n%20%5C,%20x)%7D%7Bn%7D%20&amp;%20%5Ctext%7BExchanged%20limits%7D%5C%5C%0A%20%20%20%20&amp;%20=%20%5Cbeta%20%5Csqrt%7B%5Clog%202%7D%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> which is the correct result!</p>
