<h1>Appendix</h1>
<section id="understanding-minimization-of-gcdot-via-toy-model" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="understanding-minimization-of-gcdot-via-toy-model">Understanding minimization of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(%5Ccdot)"> via toy model</h2>
<p>In order to understand this oddity, we can examine a toy example. Consider the integral <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20Z(n)%20=%20%5Cint%20e%5E%7B-(N/2)%20%5Csum_%7B(ab)%7D%20Q_%7Bab%7D%5E2%7D%20%5Cprod_%7B(ab)%7D%20dQ_%7Bab%7D%20=%20%5Cleft%20(%5Cfrac%7B2%5Cpi%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Cright)%5E%7Bn(n-1)/4%7D%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(ab)"> runs over all unordered pairs of indices <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?a,b%20%5Cin%20%5C%7B1,...,n%5C%7D"> with <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?a%5Cneq%20b">. For example: all unordered pairs of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B1,2,3,4%5C%7D"> is <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%7B(1,2),(1,3),(1,4),(2,3),(2,4),(3,4)%5C%7D">; meaning it’s equivalent to <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Csum_%7Bi%20%3C%20j%7D">.</p>
<p>Anyways, in our case <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(Q)%20=%20-%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%20%5Csum_%7Ba%3Cb%7DQ%5E2_%7Bab%7D">. If we assume the saddle point is dominated by the replica-symmetric point <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q%5E*_%7Bab%7D%20=%20q_0"> for <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?a%5Cneq%20b">. We get <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20g(Q%5E*)%20=%20-%20n(n-1)q_0%5E2%20/4%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> To recover the <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Z(n=0)%20=%201"> limit, we should make <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?q_0%20=%200">. However, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?q_0%20=%200"> corresponds to when <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?g(Q%5E*,%20q_0%20=%200)"> is minimized. Hmm…</p>
<p>Mezard &amp; Montanari explain this by saying that the number of degrees of freedom become negative when <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%20%3C%201">. But it isn’t clear to me if this reason generalizes, and what the implications are.</p>
</section>
<section id="saddle-point" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="saddle-point">Saddle Point</h2>
<p>The saddle point approximation is for estimating integrals of the form <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20I%20=%20%5Cint%20e%5E%7B-f(x)%7D%20dx%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> The idea is that the exponential will pick out the minimum of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(x)"> and exponentially kill other contributions. We can get an analytic result if we Taylor expand <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f(x)"> to second order around it’s minimum <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x_0"> <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20f(x)%20%5Capprox%20%20f(x_0)%20+%20%5Ccancel%7Bf'(x_0)%7D%20x_0%20+%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7B2%7D%20f''(x_0)%20(x%20-%20x_0)%5E2%20+%20%5Cmathcal%20O(x%5E3)%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"> Plugging this into the integral, we get a gaussian <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Balign%7D%0A%20%20%20%20I%20%5Capprox%20e%5E%7B-f(x_0)%7D%20%5Cint%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7Bf''(x_0)%7D%7B2%7D(x-x_0)%5E2%7D%20dx%20=%20e%5E%7B-f(x_0)%7D%20%5Csqrt%7B%5Cfrac%7B2%5Cpi%7D%7Bf''(x_0)%7D%7D%0A%5Cend%7Balign%7D"></p>
</section>
